photos.description: Facing northeastward and upstream. This view of the Neuse River at pretty high water on a sultry summer afternoon captures, for me at least, the very essence of the lush Atlantic Coastal Plain and its unambitious streams. The verdant bottomland-forest community, the limpid sediment-laden water, the hazy sky—just what one would expect in this corner of the world. But, as usual, appearances are deceiving. Here the Neuse has managed to cut down and expose, on the southwestern bank, a cliff approximately 80 ft (24 m) high. The reason the cliff isn't visible here is that I'm standing on top of it. Most of the exposure reveals a portion of the remarkable Late Cretaceous Black Creek Formation, a layer-cake of strata of unconsolidated sands and clays. These document transgressions of the Atlantic Ocean over the Coastal Plain, a consequence of rising global sea level. And above the Black Creek are Tertiary beds capped by Quaternary sands and gravels. As far as the botany goes, I think I'll just stand back here and enjoy it in aggregate. And what a wonderful panorama of rampant photosynthesis it truly is. One day not far removed, this place will be under saltwater again. It's best to enjoy the terrestrial phase while one still can. The other photos and descriptions of this series can be found in my Botany of the Carolinas Coastal Plain album.
photos.title: Botany of the Carolinas Coastal Plain, Part 18: Up a Not-So-Lazy River, Cliffs of the Neuse State Park, North Carolina, USA

photos.description:
Over 50,000 thousand years ago a meteor approximately 150 feet wide and weighing several hundred thousand tons slammed into the earth near Flagstaff, Arizona.  The result of the impact was the creation of a crater which measures 550 feet deep and almost a mile wide.

Meteor Crater is privately owned and is not cheap to visit.  The Museum provides an interesting history of crater geology.  One theory was that the meteor was buried deep in the earth.  The competing theory was that it exploded upon impact.  After digging down a few thousand feet, no meteor was found.  So the explosion theory won.    

Happy Fence Friday!
photos.title: Meteor Crater

photos.description: Facing southward, toward the northern-elevation facade. A cobblestone house this fine deserves another admiring look from the sidewalk. This time the perspective is full frontal. This photo should be of intense and persistent interest to astronomers because it includes, at upper center, actual visible beams of photons emitted some time before by a G-type Main Sequence star. Not many photographers have the skill to include these elusive shafts of light in their images, probably because they're too well trained or have ten times the photo equipment I do. Regarding the source star, many of you stargazers are no doubt thinking I'm referring to Tau Ceti or Alpha Centauri, but you're wrong there. The beams were a-streamin' from Old Sol. This fusion-powered gasbag hosts a planetary system inhabited, in one place, by vicious little bipeds with very limited staying power in the evolutionary record. Steer clear of them, if you value your money, your sanity, or your life. But having placed this endearing bit of architecture in its cosmic setting, let me reiterate that its cobbles most likely were collected from Pleistocene Henry Formation outwash available nearby. The basement, plinth, or foundation—whichever you wish to call it—is made of rock ashlar blocks. Given the Herrick House's completion year, these are almost certainly Ordovician-period Platteville-Galena Dolostone. It was quarried from an early date in Rockford and other Rock River Valley communities. A close-up will follow. To peruse the other photos and descriptions of this series, visit my Geology of Fieldstone & Cobblestone Buildings album.
photos.title: Geology of Fieldstone & Cobblestone Buildings, Part 20: Another Overall View of the Herrick House, Rockford, Illinois, USA (1847)

photos.description:
Shiprock rises 1,582 feet from the desert plain.  Its peak is 7,177 feet above sea level.  In Navajo its name is Winged Rock.  In Navajo legend it is the great bird that brought the Navajo people from the north to their present lands.  Its English name derives from the resemblance to a 19th century clipper ship.  

Shiprock is a volcanic plug created when magma hardens within a vent of a volcano.  Surrounding material eroded away revealing the plug.  Shiprock also has wall like dikes that radiate 5 miles south from the central formation.  Shorter dikes travel north and west.  

Shiprock has been a climbing attraction although it has been illegal to climb it since 1970.  The idea of climbing the peak is repugnant to most Navajo given its central role in legend and religious ceremonies.
photos.title: Shiprock

photos.description: Facing northeastward at the western (facade) and southern elevations. Behold a classic example of a false-front building. All that gleaming white terra-cotta, which makes this former fish market look so classy from directly ahead, turns out to be only facade-deep. But this seemingly deceitful technique of putting the fancy stuff up forward and using less costly materials on the sides and back is nothing new. Some of the world's most opulent palaces and mansions are false-fronters, too, and it's such a time-honored practice that I wouldn't be surprised if it dates back to the very origins of human architecture. In this case, of course, it would have helped if this building had neighboring structures that would make its common-brick sidewalls less obvious to passersby. But concerning that brick, note its light-yellow tint. It could be an example of Milwaukee's famous Cream City Brick, but there were few producers of it left by the mid-1920s, and by the end of that decade all were gone. Chicago Common Brick, used throughout the region, had outcompeted it. There were, however, bricks of the same color manufactured in both Kenosha and Racine, just up the coast. But the Racine yards were rapidly running out of clay and going out of business by the 1910s. As far as Kenosha Brick went, there had been at least three brickyards making it from the late nineteenth to the early twentieth centuries, but whether any of them survived into the 1920s, I don't know. Regardless, clays found in brickyards all the way from Milwaukee to Lake County, Illinois shared the same quirk of geochemistry—an unusually high amount of calcium and magnesium—that gave them their pale color. Nowadays, as the Ansorge Fish Market demonstrates, it's very difficult to tell where cream brick on buildings of southeastern-Wisconsin towns definitively came from, if there are no records to provide provenance. To see the other photos and descriptions of this series, visit my Terra-Cottalogy album.
photos.title: The Geology of Terra-Cotta, Part 15: Putting One's Best Face Forward, the Ansorge Fish Market Building, Kenosha, Wisconsin, USA (ca. 1922)

photos.description:
This image shows detail of one of the dendritic "trees" in the Fractal Forest in a straight-down view. It was the first time I witnessed the phenomenon while water remained in part of the lake. 

Flow starts gradually at the "leaves" (right) at the tips that are barely deeper than the surface itself. These flow into channels that converge and grow till the "trunks" plant themselves in the water. 

Not counting a few old tire tracks, the perpendicular lines on the shore near the trunks seem to indicate some kind of slumping of clay layers on the gradually dipping slope. 

I think this location could be a natural laboratory for the study of flow patterns. See my Dendrites album for many more photos taken at different angles and light conditions. 

Note that in this panorama, some offset channels at top and bottom are artifacts of the panorama stitching software.
photos.title: Tree-t for geophysicists

photos.description: As promised, here we are, actually Inside one of the canyon's rock shelters excavated by natural undermining and stoping (see Part 9 of this series for an explanation of the mechanics of that). If you take a good look at the ceiling of the Pennsylvanian-subperiod (Upper Carboniferous) Pounds Sandstone Member, you'll see some significant cracking. And there are also some fairly tabular chunks of rocks that might not need a lot of encouragement to come tumbling down. In fact, standing inside a rock shelter can give one that creepy, sword-of-Damocles feeling. And of course there are those big, tilted slump blocks on the ground nearby. When they came down, there must have been quite a thump. Still, if you're at Bell Smith in the early spring when sunlit water droplets are spilling like a string of diamonds over a ledge nearby, you're overtaken—to crib from Keats—with a sense of silence and slow time. For more on this beautiful and geologically fascinating locale, get a copy of my Geology Underfoot in Illinois. And to see the other photos and descriptions of this series, visit my Natural History: Illinois album.
photos.title: The Bounty of Bell Smith Springs, Part 10: Room with a View, Shawnee National Forest, Illinois, USA

photos.description: Trying to get a grasp on this memorial's two fine granitoids. Both, I believe, are feldspar-challenged, but in opposite ways. In Part 12 of this set I described the geologic origins and petrology of the red, Paleoproterozoic Montello Granite shown here. But at this range we can really examine its mineralogical components. The two dominant ingredients are the alkali feldspar orthoclase, here in its ruddiest, brick-red form, and very clear and glassy quartz. Accounting for as much as 40 percent of the rock, it's the mineral that makes the Montello so cussedly hard and enduring. Of course, there are also traces of darker compounds—hornblende, magnetite, hematite, and chlorite. In the Montello, Wisconsin quarry where this stone comes from there were a number of places where there were large veins of solid hematite and quartz that had to be worked around. However, there's also something missing here. "Normal" granites have, in addition to alkali feldspars, plagioclase feldspars. The Montello has none of the latter. That pegs it as an alkali-feldspar granite, which is a type that most usually forms in "extensional tectonic settings"—in other words, in portions of continental crust subject to tension (or being pulled apart) rather than compression. And now that we're this close, I'd be willing to bet that the salt-and-pepper stone under the Montello is the Devonian-period Barre Granodiorite (the "Barre Granite" of architects and monument makers). In terms of its grain size and biotite flecking, it's a dead ringer for it. And besides, the Barre is America's champion monumental stone. It's everywhere else, so why not here? If my assignment is correct, the lower rock you see here is notable not for having a dearth of plagioclase, but for having a preponderance of it, in the form of white oligoclase or albite. There is some alkali feldspar present, but not much. Much more in evidence are the black biotite mica and the quartz, which is this case is gray rather than transparently clear. To see the other photos and descriptions of this series, visit Architectural Geology: Southwestern Wisconsin album.
photos.title: Architectural Geology of Southwestern Wisconsin, Part 15: Zooming in on the Soldiers' and Sailors' Civil War Monument, Monroe, Wisconsin, USA (1913)

photos.description:
PANCAKE ROCKS & BLOWHOLES
Rising from the sea at Dolomite Point, the Pancake Rocks are part of a heavily eroded limestone area where the sea bursts through underwater channels and escapes via vertical blowholes.

These rocks, dating back some 30 million years, formed as layers on the sea bed which eventually rose under seismic action. Since then water, wind and salt spray have been constantly eroding the softer layers leaving a ‘pancake’ stack of harder limestone.

photos.description: Taken just south of the Temple of Athena. We're looking southward. It's always good, after staring at human works too long and closely, to step back and regain a truer sense of scale. This shot offers a half-century-old view of the Paestum archaeological site and the broad alluvial plain laid down by the Sele River since the Pleistocene. The Second Temple of Hera stands in the middle ground. It eclipses the First, behind it. In the distance, the mountains of the Cilentan coast rise in a classic Mediterranean salt haze. The scene reminds me of all those summer days I spent in the lush and verdant landscape of the Italian countryside. At certain moments the breeze stilled and there was a sort of hushed and ancient majesty hanging in the air. I have rarely found it elsewhere. And speaking of the haze, let's praise its source. The Mediterranean, that incomparable body of water, is approximately as long as the continent-spanning United States is wide. Unlike most "seas," which sit atop continental shelves or carbonate platforms, the Med is underlain by ocean crust, and is the largest remaining remnant of the great Tethys Ocean of the Mesozoic and early Cenozoic eras. The Med's characteristically opalescent sky tones are the result of a high concentration of salt crystals suspended in the lower atmosphere. This in turn is due to the sea's high salinity, caused by its often-sunny climate and its paucity of outlets to the world ocean. The other photos and descriptions of this series are ready for your inspection in my Architectural Geology: Italy album.
photos.title: Architectural Geology of Paestum, Part 4: Taking the Long View, Magna Graecia, Campania, Italy

photos.description: If you're wondering what the tiny white dots in this image are, magnify the photo and you'll see they're that kind of little white Italian Christmas lights that in the US are usually strung over trees in shopping-center parking lots. Because they're Italian, they're supposed to be all high-toned and classy, and not at all as common and tacky as colored lights or illuminated plastic Frosty the Snowman figures. Personally, I'd like to see two Frosties here, standing in the windows of the CITY HALL inset. Now that would be a winter light show to write home about, eh? Ya, you betcha. Our last look at this arrestingly red edifice zooms in a bit and shows that the locally quarried Jacobsville Sandstone certainly makes a decent carving medium. There are various brands of Upper Michigan's Jacobsville and Wisconsin's Bayfield Group sandstones that come under the general architectural heading of Lake Superior Brownstone. Some, like the "Portage Red" variety of the Jacobsville, are a cheerful brick-red, very similar in tint to the Marquette Brick shown here. But most, like the rock on display here, are a morose maroon that appealed in some very deep and chthonic way to the designers of the Richardsonian Romanesque and other nineteenth-century styles that eschewed the Greco-Roman ideal in favor of more Medieval-derived designs. And I must admit it really appeals to me, too. Incidentally, take a good look at the ashlar blocks that form the pilasters on the sides. I think they're supposed to be rusticated, sort of. At any rate, they show some of the pale, reduction-zone banding and mottling found on lower-grade Jacobsville. But Holy Wah! That Super-Dooper Yooper Marquette Brick really knocks your socks off, eh? To see the other photos and descriptions of this series, visit The Brownstone Chronicles album.

photos.description: My friend, Sævar, held his birthday party in the highlands of Iceland, in Kjölur. We went on hiking in Hveradalir, Kerlingarfjöll, and as he walked faster than I and my friends he was already on the other side waving when we were taking pictures and slowly hiking in his footsteps. Hveradalir geothermal Area is located in the Highlands, by Kjolur Highland Road, in Iceland. One of the largest geothermal areas in all of Iceland, Hveradalir offers hot springs you can view up close and others that can be admired from a safe distance. The site is surrounded by the rhyolite mountains of the Kerlingarfjoll range, making for some spectacular and colorful surroundings and excellent hiking opportunities. Situated by the volcanic mountain ridge of Kerlingarfjoll, Hveradalir draws its name from the many hot springs in the area. From smaller, bubbling mud pools to larger springs of steaming water, the site offers visitors a glimpse into the stunning complexities of Iceland's geology. One of Hveradalir's main attractions is the many striking natural formations created by the geothermal energy coursing beneath the surface. The hot waters flowing through the ground have interacted with the minerals, causing chemical changes that often result in unique patterns and colors appearing in the rocks above. Read more here: guidetoiceland.is/travel-iceland/drive/hveradalir

photos.description: The late-afternoon shadows have gobbled up the canyon floor and part of the sheer Mexican cliff across the Rio Grande. But the most important geology is still well illumined. Boquillas Canyon, that great river-gouged passage through the Sierra del Carmen, exposes a massive vertical section of the Lower Cretaceous Santa Elena Limestone. What it and the other rock units of this spectacularly beautiful mountain range have been through since they were laid down is mindboggling. Deposited as layers of lime mud in the ocean-filled breach between the recently parted North and South America, they were later—in the Upper Cretaceous and Lower Tertiary— scrunched into a giant, steplike monocline. This was one local episode of far-ranging crustal compression associated with the Laramide Orogeny. Then, in the Upper Tertiary and continuing to about 2 Ma ago, these formations were subjected to the opposite type of tectonics as part of the Rio Grande Rift / Basin-and-Range stage. Like the Laramide mountain-building event before it, the Basin-and-Range activity affected a huge portion of western North America. But this time the crust was pulled apart rather than compressed.. Here in Big Bend, about 500 mi (800 km) from the Gulf of California and the San Andreas transform fault, you'll find some of the easternmost evidence of both great tectonic phases. To wit: the big diagonal scar so nicely delineated by the low-angle light. It marks a slippage between the rock units on the left side (the headwall, sliding downward along the incline) and those on the right (the footwall, with relative upward motion). This arrangement indicates that the giant gash is a normal fault, the type characteristic of crustal stretching. So it's a later, Basin-and-Range feature rather than an earlier Laramide structure. Faults like this are rarely so beautifully exposed as classic textbook examples. But then this is Big Bend, where nature has worked overtime to create an endless collection of outrageously visible wonders. Any person devoted to any aspect of natural history could spend ten lifetimes in this magical place and still want an eleventh. To see the other photos and descriptions in this set and my other Big Bend series, visit my my Natural History: Big Bend Region & All of Trans-Pecos Texas album.
photos.title: From Persimmon Gap to Boquillas Canyon, Part 13: Oh, What a Beautiful Faulting; Big Bend National Park, Texas, USA

photos.description: Facing southwestward from the southern boundary of this renowned archaeological site's Roman settlement. The whitewashed town in the middle ground is Duqqat al-Jadida (Nouvelle Dougga). This shot offers a different perspective on the landscape surrounding Dougga. Check out Part 1 of this series, taken instead from the Roman theater situated to the northeast of this vantagepoint. The geology at close hand consists of the Mausoleum of Ateban and the ruins of the considerably younger Imperial Roman town (mostly 2nd century AD). Apparently both are made of the very locally quarried, nummulitic carbonate rock known as the El Garia Limestone. It dates, as the Mediterranean Basin's nummulite-bearing formations generally do, to the Eocene epoch. The Tunisian steppe beyond is part of what geologists call the Diapir Zone. In this portion of the North African crust, large masses of buoyant, low-density evaporite deposits of Triassic age are rising through younger host rock, and in various places have deformed it in interesting ways. Of course, this is not readily evident as one gazes across this particular scene. What is obvious, though, are the many groves of Olea europaea—Olive trees—including the one surrounding Ateban's tomb, also known as the Libyco-Punic Mausoleum. To see the other photos and descriptions in this series, visit my Architectural Geology: Tunisia album.

photos.description: Facing eastward and looking at the western elevation and central dome. Sometimes beautiful old things come in new packages—the opposite, I suppose, of the timeworn adage about new wine in old bottles. In this case, it's overtly obvious what's newer and what's older by quite a few centuries. Not surprisingly, given my geological slant, I'm more interested in the dome and the rocky core of the building beneath it. If Athens had four thousand Middle Byzantine churches, all built to the standard plan, I'd still want one more. I just like the style that much, and I like how the locally derived building materials play a key role in defining it. And those standard materials, all on display here behind the incongruously smooth-surfaced exonarthex, are: - the terra-cotta roofing tiles, no doubt made of Attica's legendary potters' clay; -bricks in a surprising variety of dimensions; - and Pliocene poros marly limestone, from Piraeus or Megara, with its pitted and puckered appearance. Once again the bricks are used to create the superb window-arch ornament, and in addition they serve as the spacers between the ashlar blocks to produce that signature effect of Athenian medieval architecture—cloisonné masonry. To see the other photos and descriptions in this series, visit my Byzantine and Late Roman Worlds album.
photos.title: Architectural Geology of Byzantine Athens, Part 11: St. Catherine Church (late 11th to early 12th century AD; rebuilt in 1927)
